    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-06-26T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-06-26T18:00:00-05:00" n="631"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d631">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.20/754: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-06-26T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 26, 1942—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>562. Department’s 253, April 3, 5 p.m. and your despatch 354, April 8.<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d631fn4">Latter not printed; it enclosed copy of a note to the
                        Chinese Ministry for Foreign Affairs dated April 8, carrying out
                        instructions contained in Department’s telegram No. 253, April 3, 5 p.m., to
                        the Ambassador, <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>.</note> War Department reports
                    that a careful study has been made of the Chinese Government’s suggestion that a
                    volunteer corps be organized from among Chinese in Hawaii. It states that a
                    substantial proportion of the Chinese in Hawaii are now performing important
                    civil defense and other duties essential to the welfare of the Territory, and
                    that others have been inducted into the armed forces. While fully appreciating
                    the sentiment of the Chinese Government, the War Department feels that it would
                    be impracticable at this time to relieve these men from their duties in order to
                    form a separate Chinese volunteer corps.</p>
                <p>In your discretion and if you consider it advisable, you may inform the Foreign
                    Office of the substance of the preceding paragraph.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
